<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
When you use another person&#8217;s ideas or words in your writing, include their name and any 
relevant page number(s), in parentheses, immediately following the cited material.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;was found to be the case (Raynal 25&#45;26).
</blockquote>
<br>
Or include the title of the work in your sentence, with the relevant page number(s) in parentheses.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Raynal suggests that &#34;the default position is markedly affected&#34; (23).
</blockquote>
<br>
When the author is referred to more than once in the same paragraph only the page number is needed 
for subsequent citations, as long as the work cannot be confused with others cited.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;was found to be the case (Raynal 25&#45;26). In addition&hellip; was a common feature (28).
</blockquote>
